We simulate the elongation of a single polymerase and the transformation of its associated transcript. The probability that an intron has spliced by the time that transcription has terminated is a function of the time it takes to cleave and polyadenylate the mRNA subsequent to the intron's synthesis, and the kinetic rate of splicing. Splicing can be modeled as a series of j sequential reactions (32). By assuming that the time of each reaction is an independent, exponentially distributed random variable with forward rate constant ks*j, we can model the probability of splicing at time t as a gamma-distributed random variable with shape j and mean 1/ks. Thus, the probability \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
