\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$P = 1.6 \times 10^{ - 4}$\end{document}).

Next, we analyzed how the combination of other CTS determinants could contribute to the higher CTS efficiency of HK genes. The model fit resulted in a higher elongation/splicing ratio in HK genes: 3.5 kb/splice compared 3.0 kb/splice in non-HK genes (Figure 4A). Interestingly, introns throughout HK genes in fact have stronger splice sites than non-HK gene introns (Figure 4C, Supplementary Figure S6A: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
