}{}$P = 6.8 \times 10^{ - 206}$\end{document}). This faster elongation/splicing ratio implies that HK genes would have lower CTS efficiency were it not for a longer post-poly(A) site delay time. As transcriptional read-through measured by GRO-seq (4.4 kb) does not account for the expected delay (equivalent to 7.3 kb), we hypothesized that transcriptional pause sites may provide additional time. Strikingly, in support of this hypothesis, HK genes have much stronger PolS2 peaks downstream of their poly(A) sites in K562 cells than non-HK genes (Figure 4E).
